  concepts:[
    {h:"Transition Metals â€” Definition & Configuration",p:"Elements with partly filled d-orbitals in ground state OR common ion. Groups 3â€“12 (3d, 4d, 5d series).<br>3d series: Sc(21) to Zn(30). Config: [Ar]3dآ¹âپ»آ¹âپ°4sâپ°âپ»آ². Exceptions: Cr=[Ar]3dâپµ4sآ¹, Cu=[Ar]3dآ¹âپ°4sآ¹ (extra stability of half-filled/fully-filled d).<br>Zn (dآ¹âپ°), Cd, Hg NOT considered true TM (Znآ²âپ؛ has dآ¹âپ°, fully filled â†’ no colour, no variable OS normally)."},
    {h:"General Properties of Transition Metals",p:"<b>Variable OS:</b> ns and (n-1)d electrons have similar energy â†’ both can be used in bonding. Mn shows +2 to +7 (widest range). Highest OS for group: Sc=+3, Ti=+4, V=+5, Cr=+6, Mn=+7.<br><b>Colour:</b> d-d electronic transitions (incomplete d subshell absorbs visible light). Cuآ²âپ؛=blue, Crآ³âپ؛=violet, Mnآ²âپ؛=faint pink. Znآ²âپ؛, Tiâپ´âپ؛ colourless (dâپ° or dآ¹âپ°).<br><b>Magnetic moment:</b> خ¼ = âˆڑ(n(n+2)) BM. n=unpaired eâپ». Mnآ²âپ؛ (5 unpaired, خ¼=5.92 BM) highest. Feآ³âپ؛ also 5.92 BM.<br><b>Catalytic activity:</b> variable OS, ability to adsorb reactants (Fe in Haber, Vâ‚‚Oâ‚… in Contact, Ni in hydrogenation).<br><b>Alloy formation:</b> similar radii â†’ substitute in lattice (steel, brass, bronze).<br><b>Interstitial compounds:</b> small atoms (H, C, N) fill voids in metal lattice â†’ very hard, high MP (TiC, WC)."},
    {h:"Important Compounds â€” KMnOâ‚„",p:"Deep purple crystals. Strong oxidising agent.<br><b>In acidic medium (Hâ‚‚SOâ‚„):</b> MnOâ‚„âپ»+8Hâپ؛+5eâپ»â†’Mnآ²âپ؛+4Hâ‚‚O (Mn: +7â†’+2, colourless). Oxidises: FeSOâ‚„, Hâ‚‚Câ‚‚Oâ‚„ (oxalic acid, used for titration), Hâ‚‚S, SOâ‚‚, Iâپ», HCl.<br><b>In neutral/alkaline medium:</b> MnOâ‚„âپ»+2Hâ‚‚O+3eâپ»â†’MnOâ‚‚+4OHâپ» (Mn: +7â†’+4, brown ppt).<br>Preparation: MnOâ‚‚+KOH+Oâ‚‚â†’Kâ‚‚MnOâ‚„ (manganate) â†’ electrolytic oxidation â†’ KMnOâ‚„.<br>Oxidation of oxalic acid: 2KMnOâ‚„+5Hâ‚‚Câ‚‚Oâ‚„+3Hâ‚‚SOâ‚„â†’2MnSOâ‚„+Kâ‚‚SOâ‚„+10COâ‚‚+8Hâ‚‚O"},
    {h:"Important Compounds â€” Kâ‚‚Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡",p:"Orange crystals. Strong oxidising agent in acidic medium.<br>Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡آ²âپ»+14Hâپ؛+6eâپ»â†’2Crآ³âپ؛+7Hâ‚‚O (Cr: +6â†’+3).<br>Oxidises: Iâپ»â†’Iâ‚‚, Feآ²âپ؛â†’Feآ³âپ؛, Hâ‚‚Sâ†’S, SOâ‚‚â†’SOâ‚ƒ, alcoholsâ†’aldehydes/acids.<br><b>pH equilibrium:</b> acidic â†’ Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡آ²âپ» (orange). Alkaline â†’ 2CrOâ‚„آ²âپ» (yellow) + Hâ‚‚O.<br>Preparation: 4FeCrâ‚‚Oâ‚„+8Naâ‚‚COâ‚ƒ+7Oâ‚‚â†’8Naâ‚‚CrOâ‚„+2Feâ‚‚Oâ‚ƒ+8COâ‚‚ â†’ acidify â†’ Naâ‚‚Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡ â†’ add KCl â†’ Kâ‚‚Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡."},
    {h:"Lanthanoids & Actinoids",p:"<b>Lanthanoids (La-Lu, 57-71):</b> 4f filling. General config: [Xe]4f^n 5d^0-1 6sآ². Mainly +3 OS (La, Ce, Pr, Nd... +3 most stable). Lanthanoid contraction: successive decrease in ionic radii of Lnآ³âپ؛ due to poor shielding of 4f electrons (imperfect shielding by f-f). Consequence: Zr & Hf have similar radii (difficult to separate), Hf denser than expected.<br><b>Actinoids (Ac-Lr, 89-103):</b> 5f filling. Show wide range of OS (+2 to +6). All radioactive. Th, U, Pa occur naturally. Uses: U-235 (nuclear fuel), Pu-239 (bomb). 5f orbitals more accessible than 4f â†’ more variable OS and covalency in actinoids."},
  ],
  mnemonics:[
    {m:"'Mn SHOWS MOST â€” +2 to +7 (widest OS range of all TMs)'",exp:"Mn: +2(MnO), +3(Mnâ‚‚Oâ‚ƒ), +4(MnOâ‚‚), +6(Kâ‚‚MnOâ‚„), +7(KMnOâ‚„)"},
    {m:"'MnOâ‚„âپ» in ACID = Mnآ²âپ؛ colourless. In BASE = MnOâ‚‚ brown.'",exp:"Acidic: purpleâ†’colourless. Alkaline: purpleâ†’brown precipitate"},
    {m:"'خ¼ = âˆڑn(n+2) BM â€” Square root, n(n+2), that's all'",exp:"n=unpaired electrons. Mnآ²âپ؛: n=5, خ¼=âˆڑ35=5.92 BM"},
    {m:"'Lanthanoid CONTRACTS because f electrons SHIELD POORLY'",exp:"4f electrons don't shield nuclear charge well â†’ ionic radii decrease across lanthanoids"},
    {m:"'Cr and Cu are EXCEPTIONS: Cr=[Ar]3dâپµ4sآ¹, Cu=[Ar]3dآ¹âپ°4sآ¹'",exp:"Extra stability of half-filled (Cr) and fully-filled (Cu) d subshell"},
  ],
  formulas:[
    {f:"خ¼ = âˆڑ(n(n+2)) BM",label:"Magnetic moment"},
    {f:"MnOâ‚„âپ»+8Hâپ؛+5eâپ»â†’Mnآ²âپ؛+4Hâ‚‚O",label:"KMnOâ‚„ in acid"},
    {f:"Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡آ²âپ»+14Hâپ؛+6eâپ»â†’2Crآ³âپ؛+7Hâ‚‚O",label:"Kâ‚‚Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡ in acid"},
  ],
  pyqs:[
    {y:"2024",m:3,q:"Why do transition metals exhibit variable oxidation states? Illustrate with Mn.",ans:"ns and (nâˆ’1)d electrons have similar energies â†’ both available for bonding/removal. Mn: [Ar]3dâپµ4sآ². Can lose 2(+2), 3(+3), 4(+4), 6(+6), 7(+7) electrons. MnO(+2), MnOâ‚‚(+4), Kâ‚‚MnOâ‚„(+6), KMnOâ‚„(+7)."},
    {y:"2023",m:3,q:"Calculate magnetic moment of (i) Feآ²âپ؛ (ii) Cuآ²âپ؛.",ans:"Feآ²âپ؛: [Ar]3dâپ¶, 4 unpaired eâپ». خ¼=âˆڑ(4أ—6)=âˆڑ24=4.90 BM. Cuآ²âپ؛: [Ar]3dâپ¹, 1 unpaired eâپ». خ¼=âˆڑ(1أ—3)=âˆڑ3=1.73 BM"},
    {y:"2022",m:3,q:"Write ionic equations for the reaction of KMnOâ‚„ with (i) FeSOâ‚„ in Hâ‚‚SOâ‚„ (ii) oxalic acid.",ans:"(i) MnOâ‚„âپ»+8Hâپ؛+5Feآ²âپ؛â†’Mnآ²âپ؛+5Feآ³âپ؛+4Hâ‚‚O (ii) 2MnOâ‚„âپ»+5Câ‚‚Oâ‚„آ²âپ»+16Hâپ؛â†’2Mnآ²âپ؛+10COâ‚‚+8Hâ‚‚O"},
    {y:"2021",m:2,q:"What is lanthanoid contraction? Give one consequence.",ans:"Successive decrease in ionic radii of lanthanoid ions (Lnآ³âپ؛) from La to Lu due to poor shielding by 4f electrons. Consequence: Zr (4d) and Hf (5d) have nearly identical radii â†’ difficult to separate."},
    {y:"2019",m:2,q:"Why are Zn, Cd, Hg not considered transition metals?",ans:"Transition metals must have partly filled d orbitals in atom or common ion. Zn/Cd/Hg: dآ¹âپ° in atom AND dآ¹âپ° in +2 ion â†’ always completely filled d â†’ not TM."},
  ],
  flashcards:[
    {q:"Magnetic moment of Mnآ²âپ؛?",a:"5.92 BM (5 unpaired electrons)",extra:"خ¼=âˆڑ(5أ—7)=âˆڑ35=5.92. Highest magnetic moment among 3d ions"},
    {q:"Colour of TM complexes is due to?",a:"d-d transition â€” electron absorbs visible light and moves between d-levels",extra:"Requires partially filled d subshell. Znآ²âپ؛(dآ¹âپ°) colourless."},
    {q:"Electronic config of Cr?",a:"[Ar] 3dâپµ 4sآ¹ (not 3dâپ´4sآ²)",extra:"Extra stability of half-filled 3dâپµ. Similarly Cu=[Ar]3dآ¹âپ°4sآ¹"},
    {q:"KMnOâ‚„ in acidic medium â€” Mn goes from?",a:"+7 to +2 (MnOâ‚„âپ» â†’ Mnآ²âپ؛, colourless)",extra:"Gains 5 electrons per MnOâ‚„âپ». Acidic medium: with Hâ‚‚SOâ‚„"},
    {q:"Kâ‚‚Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡ colour change with pH?",a:"Orange (acidic, Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡آ²âپ») â‡Œ Yellow (alkaline, CrOâ‚„آ²âپ»)",extra:"Crâ‚‚Oâ‚‡آ²âپ» + 2OHâپ» â†’ 2CrOâ‚„آ²âپ» + Hâ‚‚O"},
    {q:"Lanthanoid contraction cause?",a:"Poor shielding by 4f electrons â†’ effective nuclear charge increases across series",extra:"Consequence: Zrâ‰ˆHf in size; Period 5 TM â‰ˆ Period 6 TM in radii"},
  ]
